Absolutely! Excited to tackle this challenge with dynamic programming! We'll create a C++ program that takes user input for the length of a sequence and its values, then uses dynamic programming to find the length of the longest increasing subsequence. Let's get started!

Here's a brief outline of our approach:
1. We'll take user input for the sequence length and the sequence itself.
2. We'll use a dynamic programming array to store the length of the longest increasing subsequence ending at each index.
3. We'll iterate through the sequence, updating the dynamic programming array based on the values.
4. Finally, we'll find the maximum value in the dynamic programming array, which represents the length of the longest increasing subsequence.

Let's dive into the code!

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

int main() {
    int n;
    std::cout << "Enter the length of the sequence: ";
    std::cin >> n;

    std::vector<int> sequence(n);
    std::cout << "Enter the sequence elements: ";
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        std::cin >> sequence[i];
    }

    std::vector<int> dp(n, 1); // Initialize DP array with 1s

    // Compute the longest increasing subsequence
    for (int i = 1; i < n; ++i) {
        for (int j = 0; j < i; ++j) {
            if (sequence[i] > sequence[j]) {
                dp[i] = std::max(dp[i], dp[j] + 1);
            }
        }
    }

    // Find the maximum value in the DP array
    int maxLength = *std::max_element(dp.begin(), dp.end());

    std::cout << "The length of the longest increasing subsequence is: " << maxLength << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This program will efficiently compute the length of the longest increasing subsequence using dynamic programming. It's a great example of how dynamic programming can be used to optimize solutions to complex problems!

